"Dommenget D.","The ocean's role in continental climate variability and change",2009,"Journal of Climate","22","18",,"4939","4952",,,10.1175/2009JCLI2778.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67650509930&partnerID=40&md5=8ebe65577dc43bae2a4c662ddbfb3621","Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany","Dommenget, D., Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, D-24105 Kiel, Germany","A characteristic feature of global warming is the land-sea contrast, with stronger warming over land than over oceans. Recent studies find that this land-sea contrast also exists in equilibrium global change scenarios, and it is caused by differences in the availability of surface moisture over land and oceans. In this study it is illustrated that this land-sea contrast exists also on interannual time scales and that the ocean-land interaction is strongly asymmetric. The land surface temperature is more sensitive to the oceans than the oceans are to the land surface temperature, which is related to the processes causing the land-sea contrast in global warming scenarios. It suggests that the ocean's natural variability and change is leading to variability and change with enhanced magnitudes over the continents, causing much of the longer-time-scale (decadal) global-scale continental climate variability. Model simulations illustrate that continental warming due to anthropogenic forcing (e.g., the warming at the end of the last century or future climate change scenarios) is mostly (80%-90%) indirectly forced by the contemporaneous ocean warming, not directly by local radiative forcing. © 2009 American Meteorological Society.",,"Anthropogenic forcing; Continental climate; Future climate; Global change; Interannual time scale; Land surface temperature; Model simulation; Natural variability; Ocean warming; Radiative forcings; Surface moistures; Time-scales; Atmospheric temperature; Climatology; Global warming; Surface measurement; Surface properties; Oceanography; global change; global warming; radiative forcing; simulation; surface temperature",,,,,,"Barsugli, J.J., Battisti, D.S., The basic effects of atmosphere-ocean thermal coupling on midlatitude variability (1998) J. Atmos. Sci, 55, pp. 477-493; Brohan, P., Kennedy, J.J., Harris, I., Tett, S.F.B., Jones, P.D., Uncertainty estimates in regional and global observed temperature changes: A new dataset from 1850 (2006) J. Geophys. Res, 111, pp. D12106. , doi:10.1029/2005JD006548; Cess, R.D., Intercomparison and interpretation of climate feedback processes in 19 atmospheric general circulation models (1990) J. Geophys. Res, 95 (D10), pp. 16 601-16 615; Compo, G.P., Sardeshmukh, P.D., Oceanic influences on recent continental warming (2009) Climate Dyn, 32, pp. 333-342. , doi:10.1007/s00382-008-0448-9; Dommenget, D., (2000) Large-scale SST variability in the midlatitudes and in the tropical Atlantic, p. 76. , Ph.D. thesis, MPI Examensabeit, Geosciences, University of Hamburg, 120 pp; Dommenget, D., Latif, M., Generation of hyper climate modes (2008) Geophys. Res. Lett, 35, pp. L02706. , doi:10.1029/2007GL031087; Folland, C.K., Sexton, D.M.H., Karoly, D.J., Johnson, C.E., Rowell, D.P., Parker, D.E., Influences of anthropogenic and oceanic forcing on recent climate change (1998) Geophys. Res. Lett, 25, pp. 353-356; Joshi, M.M., Gregory, J.M., Webb, M.J., Sexton, D.M.H., Johns, T.C., Mechanisms for the land/sea warming contrast exhibited by simulations of climate change (2007) Climate Dyn, 30, pp. 455-465. , doi:10.1007/s00382-007-0306-1; Lambert, F.H., Chiang, J.C.H., Control of land-ocean temperature contrast by ocean heat uptake (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett, 34, pp. L13704. , doi:10.1029/2007GL029755; Latif, M., Keenlyside, N.S., Bader, J., Tropical sea surface temperature, vertical wind shear, and hurricane development (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett, 34, pp. L01710. , doi:10.1029/2006GL027969; Pielke Sr., R.A., Unresolved issues with the ass